{"id":14880819,"mediaExerciseId":"038e84bb-c046-4a0c-8477-9f0dd72b9987","exerciseName":"24","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612275,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":87,"solutions":[{"id":5963287,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine the cost of goods sold for Highly Suspect Corp.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/042d5b32d7e9260b3e6aec5554eccc5f/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/042d5b32d7e9260b3e6aec5554eccc5f/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define inventory turnover.\n\n**Inventory turnover** measures how fast the company can replace its inventory.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Inventory turnover}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}} {\\text{Average Inventory}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":206,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/3de817bf3dec6b09e079a997efc00bfb/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":104,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/3de817bf3dec6b09e079a997efc00bfb/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we can determine the cost of goods sold of the company, first let us determine the current assets using the current ratio:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Current ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Current Assets}} {\\text{Current Liabilities}}\\\\ \\\\\n1.25 & = \\frac{?} {\\$415,000}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":290,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/450558534ea6bcb2c1a99a23d857f313/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":147,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/450558534ea6bcb2c1a99a23d857f313/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"By deriving the formula, the current assets can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Current Assets}& =\n \\text{Current ratio} \\times \\text{Current Liabilities}\\\\ \\\\\n& = 1.25 \\times \\$415,000\\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$518,750}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the current assets is $518,750.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Next is to determine the amount of inventory, using quick ratio:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Quick ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Current Assets - Inventory}} {\\text{Current Liabilities}}\\\\ \\\\\n0.79 & = \\frac{\\$518,750  - ? } {\\$415,000}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":254,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/f2839ad9afc50ab41e4691c062128b61/lateximg_large.png","width":847},"regular":{"height":129,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/f2839ad9afc50ab41e4691c062128b61/lateximg.png","width":424}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"By deriving the formula, inventory can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Inventory}& =\n\\text{Current Assets} -  (\\text{Quick ratio} \\times \\text{Current Liabilities})\\\\ \\\\\n& = \\$518,750 - (0.79 \\times \\$415,000) \\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$190,900}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nAs can be seen, the inventory is $190,900.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Finally, we can determine the cost of goods sold by using the inventory turnover ratio formula:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Inventory turnover}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}} {\\text{Average Inventory}}\\\\ \\\\\n9.5& = \\frac{?} {\\$190,900}\\\\ \\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":296,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/c385a9a90bfee513f6e433d4617b1410/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":150,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/c193cea4b5902cb57a77a322b6e71a00/c385a9a90bfee513f6e433d4617b1410/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"By deriving the formula, Cost of Goods Sold can be computed as follows:\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Cost of Goods Sold}& =\n \\text{Inventory turnover} \\times \\text{Average Inventory}\\\\ \\\\\n& = 9.5 \\times \\$190,900\\\\ \\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$1,813,550}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\\\nIn conclusion, the cost of goods sold is $1,813,550.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8},{"columns":[{"text":"$1,813,550.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":9}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"68f1763e-d350-4815-9e56-85f34050f357","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":9}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageT